aa(lp16
VNow, as a politician myself, standing in front of you,
p17
aVor indeed, meeting any stranger anywhere in the world,
p18
aVwhen I eventually reveal the nature of my profession,
p19
aVthey look at me as though I'm somewhere between
p20
aVa snake, a monkey and an iguana,
p21
aVand through all of this, I feel, strongly,
p22
aVthat something is going wrong.
p23
aVFour hundred years of maturing democracy,
p24
aVcolleagues in Parliament who seem to me, as individuals,
p25
aVreasonably impressive, an increasingly educated,
p26
aVenergetic, informed population, and yet
p27
aVa deep, deep sense of disappointment.
p28
aVMy colleagues in Parliament include, in my new intake,
p29
aVfamily doctors, businesspeople, professors,
p30
aVdistinguished economists, historians, writers,
p31
aVarmy officers ranging from colonels down to regimental sergeant majors.
p32
aVAll of them, however, including myself, as we walk underneath
p33
aVthose strange stone gargoyles just down the road,
p34
aVfeel that we've become less than the sum of our parts,
p35
aVfeel as though we have become profoundly diminished.
